rnance. At the same time, the US government and military, universities, and other institutions have appropriated and depoliticized these same techniques to sidestep addressing structural racism and imperialism in more substantive ways. In tracing the reparative turn's complicated and fraught genealogy, Stuelke questions reparative criticism's efficacy in ways that will prompt critics to reevaluate their own reading practices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aNeoliberalism and literaturezUnited States. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021575zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021575423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021575/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles